# mockspace-config

The canonical typed schema for mockspace.toml, extracted from `mockspace/src/config.rs` so external tools can parse and produce mockspace configurations without depending on the mockspace binary or its internal modules (design-round state machine, bench harness, dylib check, etc.).

Also defines `IntoMockspaceConfig`, the trait consumer tools implement on their own typed configs to map their schemas onto mockspace's template-context vocabulary. This is the bridge that lets a single template tree render against multiple consumer config schemas as long as each schema declares its mapping to the canonical Config.

## What this crate provides

| Item | Role |
|---|---|
| `Config` | Canonical typed struct; the template-context contract every mockspace template renders against. |
| `parse_mockspace_toml(path: &Path) -> Result<Config, ConfigError>` | Default entry point for tools that consume mockspace.toml directly. |
| `IntoMockspaceConfig` (trait) | Consumer schemas implement this to map their typed config onto Config. The trait is the abstraction that makes Config a true contract rather than a private mockspace internal. |
| `ConfigError` | Error type covering TOML parse failures, missing required fields, mapping errors. |
| `MappingError` | Sub-error type for `IntoMockspaceConfig::into_mockspace_config()` failures. |
| `InstallMode` | Enum: `Replace` / `MergeAppend` / `MergePrepend` / `Skip`. |
| `AttributionConfig` | Agent attribution policy sub-struct. |
| `MacroStyle` | Domain-specific macro labeling sub-struct. |
| `CommitStyle` | Commit message conventions sub-struct. |
| `LintConfig` | Re-export from `mockspace-lint-rules`; per-lint severity overrides. |

## The canonical Config schema

The `Config` struct is the template-context contract. Templates reference field names directly (`{{ project_name }}`, `{{ mock_dir }}`, `{{ crate_prefix }}`). Any consumer producing a Config must populate the template-visible fields; behavioral fields (install modes, ABI version) may be left at defaults when they don't apply.

| Field | Type | Visible to templates | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| `mock_dir` | `PathBuf` | yes | Path to the mockspace workspace root (typically `<repo>/mock`). |
| `crates_dir` | `PathBuf` | yes | Path to the mock workspace's crates directory. |
| `repo_root` | `PathBuf` | yes | Path to the consumer repo root. |
| `docs_dir` | `PathBuf` | yes | Path where rendered docs go. |
| `project_name` | `String` | yes | Display name for the project. |
| `crate_prefix` | `String` | yes | Common prefix for crates in the project (e.g. `arvo-`). |
| `proc_macro_crates` | `Vec<String>` | yes | Names of proc-macro crates (lint exemption candidates). |
| `lint_proc_macro_source` | `bool` | no | Whether source-scanning lints scan proc-macro source. |
| `module_crates` | `Vec<String>` | yes | Crates that publish as separate modules. |
| `unprefixed_crates` | `Vec<String>` | yes | Crates that don't carry the common prefix. |
| `abi_version` | `u32` | no | Dylib lint ABI version. |
| `nuke_marker` | `String` | no | Sentinel string for nuke-mode operations. |
| `commit_style` | `CommitStyle` | yes | Commit message conventions. |
| `install_git_hooks` | `InstallMode` | no | How mockspace-managed git hooks are installed. |
| `install_cargo_config` | `InstallMode` | no | How `.cargo/config.toml` is installed. |
| `install_agent_files` | `InstallMode` | no | How `.claude/` and `.github/` agent files are installed. |
| `attribution` | `AttributionConfig` | yes | Agent attribution policy. |
| `lint_overrides` | `LintConfig` | no | Per-lint severity overrides. |
| `domain_kinds` | `BTreeMap<String, String>` | yes | Domain-specific macro labeling. |

The "visible to templates" column distinguishes:
- **yes**: the field affects template-rendered output. Mapped configs MUST populate this field for templates to work.
- **no**: behavioral / lint-config / install-mode only. Mapped configs MAY use defaults if the consumer tool doesn't need the behavior.

## parse_mockspace_toml

The default entry point for tools that already speak mockspace.toml:

```rust
use mockspace_config::{parse_mockspace_toml, Config, ConfigError};
use std::path::Path;

let cfg: Config = parse_mockspace_toml(Path::new("mockspace.toml"))?;
```

The function reads the file, deserializes via `serde + toml`, validates required fields are present, and returns a typed `Config`.

`ConfigError` variants cover:
- File not found
- TOML parse error (with line/column from the toml crate)
- Required field missing or wrong type
- Cross-field validation failure (e.g. `crates_dir` not a subpath of `mock_dir`)

## IntoMockspaceConfig trait

The trait that makes Config a portable contract. Any consumer typed config implements this to produce a Config from their schema.

```rust
pub trait IntoMockspaceConfig {
    /// Convert this typed config into a canonical mockspace Config.
    ///
    /// Returns MappingError if the source schema lacks information needed
    /// to populate a required Config field (e.g. mock_dir not derivable
    /// from the source).
    fn into_mockspace_config(self) -> Result<Config, MappingError>;
}

/// Identity impl: a Config is already a Config.
impl IntoMockspaceConfig for Config {
    fn into_mockspace_config(self) -> Result<Config, MappingError> {
        Ok(self)
    }
}
```

### Why a trait, not a serde-driven path-rewrite mechanism

Trait-based mapping is compile-time-checked: a consumer's typed config evolves in lockstep with their Rust types, and the IDE catches missing fields at the trait-impl site. Serde-driven path-rewrite would be data-shaped (a `.toml` mapping file) which is more flexible but accepts no compile-time guarantee that the mapping is complete. For the workspace's "one tool, one schema" usage pattern, compile-time correctness wins; data-driven mapping has no concrete consumer driving it.

### Example: a consumer impl

This is the forward-reference shape homma will implement once `mockspace-config` ships:

```rust
use mockspace_config::{Config, IntoMockspaceConfig, MappingError, CommitStyle};
use std::path::PathBuf;

#[derive(Debug, Clone, serde::Deserialize)]
pub struct HommaConfig {
    pub workspace: WorkspaceSection,
    // ... other homma-specific sections
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, serde::Deserialize)]
pub struct WorkspaceSection {
    pub root: PathBuf,
    pub name: String,
}

impl IntoMockspaceConfig for HommaConfig {
    fn into_mockspace_config(self) -> Result<Config, MappingError> {
        Ok(Config {
            mock_dir: self.workspace.root.join("mock"),
            crates_dir: self.workspace.root.join("mock/crates"),
            repo_root: self.workspace.root.clone(),
            docs_dir: self.workspace.root.join("docs"),
            project_name: self.workspace.name,
            crate_prefix: String::new(),
            commit_style: CommitStyle::default(),
            // ... defaults for behavioral fields homma doesn't use
            ..Config::default()
        })
    }
}
```

### When a mapping is impossible

If a consumer's schema genuinely lacks the information to produce a valid Config (e.g. no project_name field), the impl returns `MappingError::MissingField { name }`. The consumer then knows their schema needs extending, or the template they want to render is incompatible with their config shape.

## What this crate does NOT do

| Concern | Where it lives |
|---|---|
| Non-mockspace TOML schema (homma.toml etc.) | The consumer crate (homma in this case) |
| Template engine | `mockspace-template` |
| Mockspace-binary-specific state (design rounds, bench harness, dylib check) | mockspace internals |
| Configuration validation beyond basic schema check | future work tracked in `BACKLOG.md.tmpl` |

## Crate dependencies

- `serde` + `serde_derive` — struct deserialization
- `toml` — TOML parsing
- `mockspace-lint-rules` — `LintConfig` re-export (already a workspace crate)
- `std` — `PathBuf`, `BTreeMap`, `io::Result`

No `notko` / `arvo` / `hilavitkutin`. (Same rationale as mockspace-template; substrate adoption deferred to live-port.)

## Audit trail

- `mockspace/src/config.rs` — current canonical Config implementation (~674 lines); this crate ports a stripped, decoupled version preserving the field shape.
- `mockspace/src/parse.rs` — TOML parsing helpers; relevant bits port into this crate's `parse_mockspace_toml`.

